# IWSDK Typed API Quick Reference

Confirm a member or signature here instead of casting to `any`. `World`, `World.create` options, every sub-manager, and the `Entity`/component surfaces are **fully typed** — a TS error is a real bug (wrong key/member), not a framework typing gap. If a symbol isn't here, run `npx iwsdk reference api|systems|components` (see the bottom of this file) before guessing.

## Contents

- World members
- WorldOptions key + type table
- System surface
- Entity surface
- Input
- Components catalog
- Wrong-name → real-name table

## World members

All of these are public, typed members of `World` (`packages/core/src/ecs/world.ts`). Never `(world as any)` — casting strips autocomplete and silently masks wrong paths (`(world as any).ecs?.registerSystem?.(...)` and `(world as any).render?.camera` no-op; there is no `world.ecs` or `world.render` at runtime).

```typescript
world.scene; // Scene
world.camera; // PerspectiveCamera — the active camera in BOTH browser and XR
world.renderer; // WebGLRenderer (three)
world.input; // InputManager (see Input below)
world.player; // XROrigin Group (player rig)
world.playerEntity; // Entity wrapping the XROrigin Group
world.cameraEntity; // Entity wrapping the camera
```

**Active camera:** use `world.camera`. It is parented to the player rig and is what the render loop passes to `renderer.render(scene, camera)`, so its world transform tracks the headset during a session. Do **not** traverse the scene graph (`scene.getObjectByProperty('isCamera', …)`, a `findCamera()` helper) or reach for `renderer.xr.getCamera()` in app code. Example — screen-pointer raycast:

```typescript
raycaster.setFromCamera(new Vector2(ndcX, ndcY), world.camera);
```

### ECS-native player rig

```typescript
world.playerEntity; // Entity wrapping XROrigin Group
world.playerHeadEntity; // Entity for head space
world.playerSpaceEntities; // { head, raySpaces, gripSpaces, indexTipSpaces }
```

`playerSpaceEntities` values are **Entities**; the `Object3D` is the `.object3D` PROPERTY (there is no `getObject3D()` method). Each space group is `{ left, right }`. Spaces are only valid in an active XR session — gate on `world.input.xr` / session state.

```typescript
const grip = world.playerSpaceEntities.gripSpaces.right.object3D; // Object3D | undefined
const pos = new Vector3();
grip?.getWorldPosition(pos); // world-space controller position
grip?.add(saber.group); // parent content directly to the grip space
```

### Registration & entity factories

System / component registration is chainable and typed — call it on `world`, not a fictional `world.ecs`:

```typescript
world.registerComponent(MyComponent).registerSystem(MySystem);
world.registerSystem(GameLoopSystem); // register the CLASS, not an instance
const loop = world.getSystem(GameLoopSystem)!; // typed instance back
```

`createTransformEntity(object?, parentOrOptions?)` returns an `Entity` whose `.object3D` is **optional** (`Object3D | undefined`). It always sets `object3D` (falls back to `new Object3D()` when you pass nothing), so a non-null assertion is correct right after creation; guard when iterating queries.

```typescript
const hud = world.createTransformEntity(hudMesh, {
  parent: world.playerHeadEntity,
  persistent: true,
});
hud.object3D!.position.set(0, 1.5, -2); // ! is correct: just created it
// in a long-lived loop: if (!entity.object3D) continue;
```

## WorldOptions key + type table

`World.create(container, options)` — `container` is an `HTMLElement`. The options bag is typed (`WorldOptions`, `packages/core/src/init/world-initializer.ts`); it typechecks as-is — never blanket-cast it to `any`. If one key errors with `TS2353`, fix that one key.

| Key                   | Type                                                                                           | Notes                                                                                                                      |
| --------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `xr`                  | `false \| { offer?: 'none' \| 'once' \| 'always', ... }`                                       | `offer: 'once'` is a string-union literal — needs **no** `as const`, **no** `as any`. `xr: false` = browser-first.         |
| `render`              | `{ fov?, near?, far?, defaultLighting?, stencil?, camera? }`                                   | —                                                                                                                          |
| `render.camera`       | `{ position?, rotation?, quaternion?, lookAt? }`                                               | All `[x,y,z]` (`quaternion` is `[x,y,z,w]`); sets initial local pose under `world.player`.                                 |
| `input`               | `{ canvasPointerEvents? }`                                                                     | `canvasPointerEvents`: `boolean \| { enabled?, activeDuringXR? }`.                                                         |
| `features`            | `{ grabbing, locomotion, physics, sceneUnderstanding, environmentRaycast, camera, spatialUI }` | Each `boolean` (some accept an object — see below).                                                                        |
| `features.locomotion` | `boolean \| { ..., browserControls?, turningMethod?, enableJumping?, ... }`                    | `browserControls`: `boolean \| { keyboard?, gamepad?, pointerLock? }` (WASD/arrows + Space + gamepad; app owns mouselook). |

```typescript
// Browser-first world (no XR)
const world = await World.create(container, {
  xr: false,
  render: {
    near: 0.001,
    far: 200,
    camera: { position: [0, 1.6, 0], lookAt: [0, 1.55, -1] },
  },
  input: { canvasPointerEvents: true },
  features: {
    grabbing: true,
    locomotion: { browserControls: true },
    physics: true,
  },
});
```

## System surface

`World.create` already starts the render/update loop (the XR session loop in immersive mode). Put **all** per-frame game logic in a registered `System`. Do not hand-roll `requestAnimationFrame`, call `renderer.setAnimationLoop`, or override `world.update`.

`createSystem(queries, configSchema)` is the imported factory used as a **base class**; both args are optional. The per-frame method MUST be named `update` and its args are in **seconds**.

```typescript
import { createSystem, World } from '@iwsdk/core';

export class GameLoopSystem extends createSystem({
  balls: {
    required: [
      /* components */
    ],
  },
}) {
  private game!: GameManager;

  init() {
    /* one-time setup; runs once on register */
  }

  // Inject app collaborators with a setter — the ENGINE constructs the system,
  // so you cannot pass them through a constructor.
  setRefs(refs: { game: GameManager }) {
    this.game = refs.game;
  }

  // The per-frame tick. Name MUST be `update`. Args are in SECONDS, not ms.
  update(delta: number, time: number) {
    this.game.update(delta);
    this.queries.balls.entities.forEach((e) => {
      /* ... */
    });
    if (this.input.keyboard.getKeyDown('Space')) {
      /* ... */
    }
  }
}

world.registerSystem(GameLoopSystem);
const loop = world.getSystem(GameLoopSystem)!;
loop.setRefs({ game });
```

`this.*` members (world resources are already on `this` inside a system):

`this.world`, `this.scene`, `this.camera`, `this.renderer`, `this.input`, `this.player`, `this.playerEntity`, `this.queries`, `this.config`.

**Queries:** `this.queries.<name>.entities` is the iterable result set. Subscribe to lifecycle edges with `this.queries.<name>.subscribe('qualify', cb)` (fires the frame an entity first matches — the deterministic ready hook for async-loaded `PanelDocument`; see references/troubleshooting.md and the PanelUI rule). Scope a query per-config with `where: [eq(Component, 'field', value)]`.

## Entity surface

`Entity` methods (`packages/core/src/ecs/entity.ts`):

| Member          | Signature                          | Notes                                                                                                                |
| --------------- | ---------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `addComponent`  | `addComponent(Component, data?)`   | Attaches a component (and optional initial data).                                                                    |
| `getValue`      | `getValue(Component, key)`         | Reads a field.                                                                                                       |
| `setValue`      | `setValue(Component, key, value)`  | Writes a field. Built-ins re-read fields live each frame — update in place, do **not** remove + re-add to "refresh". |
| `getVectorView` | `getVectorView(Component, key)`    | Live `Float32Array` view of a vec field (e.g. `getVectorView(PhysicsBody, '_linearVelocity')`).                      |
| `hasComponent`  | `hasComponent(Component)`          | e.g. `if (e.hasComponent(Pressed)) ...`.                                                                             |
| `object3D`      | `Object3D \| undefined` (property) | Guard or `!`-assert; show/hide via `entity.object3D!.visible`, never move panels off-screen.                         |

There is **NO** `setComponentValue` (calling it silently no-ops — use `setValue`). There is **NO** `getObject3D()` method — use the `.object3D` property. (`iwsdk ecs set-component` is the _CLI_ surface; the in-code equivalent is `setValue`.)

## Input

`world.input` is `InputManager`; all sub-managers are typed (never `(world.input as any)`).

```typescript
world.input.xr; // XRInputManager (controllers, hands)
world.input.keyboard; // StatefulKeyboard (on world.input, NOT world.input.xr)
world.input.actions; // InputActionManager
world.input.browserGamepads; // Browser gamepad array
```

### XR controller gamepads

`world.input.xr.gamepads.left` / `.right` is `StatefulGamepad | undefined`. All `getButton*` / `getAxesValues` take a **string** id (the `InputComponent` enum value, e.g. `InputComponent.Thumbstick === 'xr-standard-thumbstick'`). Passing a **number** silently returns `undefined`. `getAxesValues(id)` returns `{ x, y } | undefined` — never an array.

```typescript
import { InputComponent } from '@iwsdk/core';

const right = world.input.xr.gamepads.right;
if (right) {
  if (right.getButtonDown(InputComponent.Trigger)) fire(); // edge: pressed this frame
  const held = right.getButtonPressed(InputComponent.Squeeze); // held this frame
  const stick = right.getAxesValues(InputComponent.Thumbstick); // { x, y } | undefined
  if (stick) aim(stick.x, stick.y); // NOT stick[0]/stick[1]
  const a = right.getButtonDown(InputComponent.A_Button);
}
```

Haptics: there is no IWSDK helper. `world.input.xr.gamepads[hand].gamepad` is the typed raw `Gamepad`; only the non-standard `pulse` call needs a cast.

```typescript
const gp = world.input.xr.gamepads[hand]?.gamepad; // typed Gamepad, no cast
const actuator = gp?.hapticActuators?.[0] as
  | { pulse?: (i: number, ms: number) => void }
  | undefined;
actuator?.pulse?.(Math.min(intensity, 1), durationMs);
```

### Keyboard (browser-first)

```typescript
world.input.keyboard.getKeyPressed('KeyW'); // held this frame
world.input.keyboard.getKeyDown('Space'); // pressed this frame
world.input.keyboard.getKeyUp('KeyE'); // released this frame
```

### Action-backed input (built-in names)

```typescript
world.input.actions.getAxis2D('locomotion.move'); // { x, y }
world.input.actions.getButtonDown('locomotion.jump');
```

Built-in action names: `locomotion.move`, `locomotion.turn`, `locomotion.jump`, `locomotion.teleportAim`, `locomotion.teleportCommit`, `interaction.select`. Some names are reserved for app/user bindings and are not default-bound.

## Components catalog

Import all from `@iwsdk/core`.

**Physics** (Havok) — `features.physics: true` only boots the engine; nothing simulates until an entity has BOTH `PhysicsShape` and `PhysicsBody`.

- `PhysicsShape` — `{ shape: PhysicsShapeType, dimensions: [x,y,z] }`.
- `PhysicsShapeType` — enum: `Sphere` / `Box` / `Cylinder` / `ConvexHull` / `Auto` (derives dimensions from the Three.js geometry).
- `PhysicsBody` — `{ state: PhysicsState }`; tuning fields `linearDamping` / `angularDamping` (drag), `gravityFactor` (0 = float, >1 = heavy). Live velocity via `getVectorView(PhysicsBody, '_linearVelocity')`.
- `PhysicsState` — enum: `Static` (walls/floors, immovable but collide), `Dynamic` (gravity + forces), `Kinematic` (you move it, it pushes others).
- `PhysicsManipulation` — one-shot, auto-removes after 1 frame: `{ force: [x,y,z] }` (impulse at center of mass) or `{ linearVelocity: [x,y,z] }` (overrides velocity).

```typescript
import {
  PhysicsBody,
  PhysicsState,
  PhysicsShape,
  PhysicsShapeType,
  PhysicsManipulation,
} from '@iwsdk/core';

const entity = world.createTransformEntity(ballMesh);
entity.addComponent(PhysicsShape, {
  shape: PhysicsShapeType.Sphere,
  dimensions: [0.2, 0.2, 0.2],
});
entity.addComponent(PhysicsBody, { state: PhysicsState.Dynamic });
entity.addComponent(PhysicsManipulation, { force: [0, 8, -3] });
const p = entity.object3D!.position; // updated by PhysicsSystem
```

**Audio** — use `AudioSource` / `AudioUtils`, not raw Web Audio (raw `AudioContext`/oscillators bypass spatial audio and the ECS `AudioSystem`).

- `AudioSource` — component: `{ src, volume, positional, ... }` (`positional: true` = distance-attenuated 3D audio with refDistance/rolloff/cone fields; `positional: false` = ambient). `loop`/`autoplay` are `AudioSource` fields.
- `AudioUtils` — `play` / `stop` / `pause` (take the entity).

```typescript
import { AudioSource, AudioUtils } from '@iwsdk/core';

const e = world.createTransformEntity(mesh);
e.addComponent(AudioSource, {
  src: '/audio/hit.mp3',
  volume: 0.8,
  positional: true,
});
AudioUtils.play(e);
```

**PanelUI / Spatial UI** — uikit elements, NOT the DOM. (Full lifecycle/authoring rules: references/troubleshooting.md.)

- `PanelUI` — added with `{ config: './ui/x.json' }` (relative path; loads async). Attaches `PanelDocument` (and queryable `UIKitDocument`) only after the load resolves.
- `PanelDocument` — holds `document` (the `UIKitDocument`); `getValue(PanelDocument, 'document')` is `undefined` for the first frames after `addComponent`.
- `UIKitDocument` — `getElementById('#id')`, `querySelector('.class')`.
- `UIKit` — namespace of concrete element types (`UIKit.Text`, ...). Narrow `getElementById` results to these; mutate via `setProperties({ ... })` (not `.textContent`/`.onclick`/`.style`); read computed values via `el.properties.value.<prop>`.

```typescript
import { PanelUI, PanelDocument, UIKitDocument, UIKit, eq } from '@iwsdk/core';

const doc = entity.getValue(PanelDocument, 'document') as
  | UIKitDocument
  | undefined;
const label = doc?.getElementById('score') as UIKit.Text | undefined;
label?.setProperties({ text: '1200' });
```

**Interaction** — do not raycast by hand; tag the target and query transient state.

- `RayInteractable` — register an entity as a ray target.
- `PokeInteractable` — register an entity as a touch/poke target.
- `Hovered` / `Pressed` — transient tags the `InputSystem` adds; query them in a system (`if (e.hasComponent(Pressed)) handleClick(e)`).

```typescript
import { RayInteractable, Pressed } from '@iwsdk/core';
entity.addComponent(RayInteractable);
// in a system over { required: [RayInteractable] }:
if (e.hasComponent(Pressed)) handleClick(e);
```

**Follower** — attaches an entity to a tracked space with an `offsetPosition` (re-read live every frame; change it with `setValue`, do not remove + re-add).

## Wrong-name → real-name table

A TS error on any of these is a real bug — never cast `world`/components to `any` to silence it.

| Wrong (guessed)                                                | Real                                                                                                                                                          |
| -------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `world.onUpdate(fn)` / `world.onFrame`                         | No such method. `World.update(delta,time)` is the engine tick the runtime calls for you — do not call, assign, or wrap it. Put per-frame logic in a `System`. |
| `world.ecs.registerSystem(...)`                                | No `world.ecs`. Use `world.registerSystem(SystemClass)`. `(world as any).ecs?.registerSystem?.(...)` silently no-ops and ships a dead loop.                   |
| `world.createSystem({...})`                                    | No such method (returns `undefined`). `createSystem(...)` is the imported factory used as a **base class**.                                                   |
| `class { execute(dt) {} }`                                     | The tick method is `update(delta, time)`, not `execute`.                                                                                                      |
| `renderer.setAnimationLoop(...)` / raw `requestAnimationFrame` | The managed loop already ticks registered systems; a manual rAF does **not** run on the XR session loop.                                                      |
| `entity.setComponentValue(C, f, v)`                            | `entity.setValue(C, f, v)` (the `set-component` form is the _CLI_ surface).                                                                                   |
| `entity.getObject3D()`                                         | `entity.object3D` (property; `Object3D \| undefined`).                                                                                                        |
| `getAxesValues(id)[0]` / `[1]`                                 | Returns `{ x, y } \| undefined` — read `.x` / `.y`.                                                                                                           |
| `getButtonDown(2)` (number id)                                 | Pass the string `InputComponent` value (`InputComponent.Thumbstick`); a number silently returns `undefined`.                                                  |
| `(world as any).render?.camera`                                | `world.camera` (`render` is a `WorldOptions` key, not a runtime member).                                                                                      |
| `world.input.gamepads`                                         | `world.input.xr.gamepads` (deprecated alias; also `.multiPointers`, `.visualAdapters`, `.isPrimary()` moved under `.xr`).                                     |

---

For anything not listed, query the live SDK rather than guessing:

```bash
npx iwsdk reference api --input-json '{"name":"World.create"}'
npx iwsdk reference systems --input-json '{}'
npx iwsdk reference components --input-json '{}'
```

# Phase 1 — World & the Game Loop

This is the costly correctness fork. Two mistakes here silently ship broken apps that still build green: a dead game loop (per-frame logic not in an ECS System) and `(world as any)` casts that mask wrong paths. Both are covered in full depth below.

## Contents

- World Creation
- WorldOptions is typed — never blanket-cast
- Dual-Runtime Pattern (XR + Browser Fallback)
- World is fully typed — never `(world as any)`
- Per-Frame Logic = ECS Systems (the ONLY supported game loop)
- ECS-Native Player Rig

> Physics, audio, asset management, and input live in `03-subsystems.md`. CLI commands (`iwsdk ecs systems`, `scene hierarchy`) live in `cli-reference.md`. Verification (`tsc --noEmit` + screenshot) lives in `troubleshooting.md`.

## World Creation

```typescript
// XR world (default)
const world = await World.create(container);

// XR world with options
const world = await World.create(container, {
  xr: { offer: 'once' }, // or 'always' / 'none'; omit xr for the default
  render: { near: 0.01, far: 200 },
  features: {
    grabbing: true,
    locomotion: true,
    physics: true,
    spatialUI: false,
  },
});

// Browser-first world (no XR)
const world = await World.create(container, {
  xr: false,
  render: {
    near: 0.001,
    far: 200,
    camera: { position: [0, 1.6, 0], lookAt: [0, 1.55, -1] },
  },
  input: { canvasPointerEvents: true },
  features: {
    grabbing: true,
    locomotion: { browserControls: true }, // WASD/arrows + Space + gamepad; app owns mouselook
    physics: true,
  },
});
```

## WorldOptions is typed — never blanket-cast

`World.create` options are **typed** (`WorldOptions`). Do not blanket-cast the options object to `any` — a type error here means a wrong key (e.g. `render` vs a runtime member), not a framework bug.

The whole bag typechecks as-is against `@iwsdk/core`. Do NOT write `await World.create(container, { ... } as any)`: a blanket cast silently masks every later misconfig. If one key errors, fix that one key. The keys are all real and typed:

- `xr`: `false | { offer?: 'none' | 'once' | 'always', ... }`. `offer: 'once'` is a string-union literal — it needs **no** `as const` and **no** `as any`.
- `render`: `{ fov?, near?, far?, defaultLighting?, stencil?, camera? }`. `render.camera` is `{ position?, rotation?, quaternion?, lookAt? }` (all `[x,y,z]`; `quaternion` is `[x,y,z,w]`) and sets the initial local pose under `world.player`.
- `input`: `{ canvasPointerEvents? }`, type `boolean | { enabled?, activeDuringXR? }`.
- `features.locomotion`: `boolean | { ..., browserControls?, turningMethod?, enableJumping?, ... }`; `browserControls` is `boolean | { keyboard?, gamepad? }`.
- `features`: `grabbing | locomotion | physics | sceneUnderstanding | environmentRaycast | camera | spatialUI`.

The container arg is an `HTMLElement`; the common pattern is `const container = document.getElementById('scene-container') as HTMLDivElement;`.

## Dual-Runtime Pattern (XR + Browser Fallback)

For games that should work both in VR and in the browser:

```typescript
const world = await World.create(container, {
  xr: { offer: 'once' },
  input: { canvasPointerEvents: true },
  features: {
    grabbing: true,
    locomotion: { browserControls: true },
    physics: true,
  },
});
```

## World is fully typed — never `(world as any)`

These are all public, typed members of `World` (`packages/core/src/ecs/world.ts`). Casting to `any` strips autocomplete and silently masks wrong paths (e.g. `(world as any).ecs?.registerSystem?.(...)` and `(world as any).render?.camera` no-op — there is no `world.ecs` or `world.render` at runtime).

```typescript
world.scene; // Scene
world.camera; // PerspectiveCamera — the active camera in BOTH browser and XR
world.renderer; // WebGLRenderer (three)
world.input; // InputManager (see Input System below)
world.player; // XROrigin Group (player rig)
world.playerEntity; // Entity wrapping the XROrigin Group
world.cameraEntity; // Entity wrapping the camera
```

**Active camera:** use `world.camera`. It is parented to the player rig and is what the render loop passes to `renderer.render(scene, camera)`, so its world transform tracks the headset during a session. Do **not** traverse the scene graph (`scene.getObjectByProperty('isCamera', …)`, a `findCamera()` helper) or reach for `renderer.xr.getCamera()` in app code. Example — screen-pointer raycast:

```typescript
raycaster.setFromCamera(new Vector2(ndcX, ndcY), world.camera);
```

**System / component registration is chainable and typed** — call it on `world`, not a fictional `world.ecs`:

```typescript
world.registerComponent(MyComponent).registerSystem(MySystem);
```

## Per-Frame Logic = ECS Systems (the ONLY supported game loop)

`World.create` already starts the render/update loop (the XR session loop in immersive mode). Put **all** per-frame game logic in a registered `System`. Do not hand-roll `requestAnimationFrame`, do not call `renderer.setAnimationLoop`, and do not override `world.update`.

```typescript
import { createSystem, World } from '@iwsdk/core';

// queries + a config schema are both optional
export class GameLoopSystem extends createSystem({
  balls: {
    required: [
      /* components */
    ],
  },
}) {
  private game!: GameManager;

  init() {
    /* one-time setup; runs once on register */
  }

  // Inject app collaborators with a setter — the ENGINE constructs the system,
  // so you cannot pass them through a constructor.
  setRefs(refs: { game: GameManager }) {
    this.game = refs.game;
  }

  // The per-frame tick. Name MUST be `update`. Args are in SECONDS, not ms.
  update(delta: number, time: number) {
    this.game.update(delta);
    this.queries.balls.entities.forEach((e) => {
      /* ... */
    });
    if (this.input.keyboard.getKeyDown('Space')) {
      /* ... */
    }
  }
}

world.registerSystem(GameLoopSystem); // register the CLASS, not an instance
const loop = world.getSystem(GameLoopSystem)!; // typed instance back
loop.setRefs({ game });
```

Inside a system, world resources are already on `this`: `this.world`, `this.scene`, `this.camera`, `this.renderer`, `this.input`, `this.player`, `this.playerEntity`, `this.queries`, `this.config`.

**These do NOT exist — a TS error here is a real bug, never "a known IWSDK typing issue." Do not cast `world` to `any` to silence it:**

| Guessed (wrong)                                                | Reality                                                                                                                                                  |
| -------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `world.onUpdate(fn)` / `world.onFrame`                         | No such method. `World.update(delta,time)` is the engine tick the runtime calls for you — do not call, assign, or wrap it.                               |
| `world.ecs.registerSystem(...)`                                | No `world.ecs`. `(world as any).ecs?.registerSystem?.(...)` silently no-ops and ships a dead loop.                                                       |
| `world.createSystem({...})`                                    | No such method (returns `undefined`). `createSystem(...)` is the imported factory used as a base class.                                                  |
| `class { execute(dt) {} }`                                     | The tick method is `update(delta,time)`, not `execute`.                                                                                                  |
| `renderer.setAnimationLoop(...)` / raw `requestAnimationFrame` | The managed loop already ticks registered systems; a manual rAF does **not** run on the XR session loop, so the game won't tick in an immersive session. |

`requestAnimationFrame`/`setTimeout` are fine for pure DOM/CSS overlays (HTML fades) outside the 3D scene — but anything touching scene state, physics, scoring, or input must run in a System. The generated starter models this: see `src/index.template.ts` (`world.registerSystem(PanelSystem).registerSystem(RobotSystem)`) and `src/robot.ts` (a `createSystem` with `update()`).

**Don't let `as any` hide a broken game loop.** A "build passes, screenshot renders" app can still have a dead loop — the classic failure is guessing an engine path, casting it away, and swallowing the error into a silent rAF fallback:

```ts
// BAD — guesses a non-existent path, then silently runs a raw rAF loop
try {
  (world as any).ecs?.registerSystem?.(UpdateSystem);
} catch {
  requestAnimationFrame(rafLoop);
}
```

The correct call is `world.registerSystem(GameLoopSystem)`. Don't wrap engine calls in `try/catch` that swallows and falls back; let them throw. After `dev up`, confirm with `npx iwsdk ecs systems` that your systems are listed — if absent, the loop is running off-ECS (see `cli-reference.md`). The ECS debug tools (`pause`/`step`/`snapshot`) only see registered Systems; a hand-rolled rAF loop is invisible to them and keeps advancing even when ECS is "paused."

## ECS-Native Player Rig

```typescript
world.playerEntity; // Entity wrapping XROrigin Group
world.playerHeadEntity; // Entity for head space
world.playerSpaceEntities; // { head, raySpaces, gripSpaces, indexTipSpaces }

// Attach a HUD to the player's head
const hud = world.createTransformEntity(hudMesh, {
  parent: world.playerHeadEntity,
  persistent: true,
});
```

`createTransformEntity` returns an `Entity` whose `.object3D` is **optional** (`Object3D | undefined`). It always sets `object3D` (it falls back to `new Object3D()` when you pass nothing), so immediately after creation you can assert (`entity.object3D!.position`); inside systems/queries where an entity may have been torn down, guard instead (`if (!entity.object3D) continue;` or `entity.object3D?.position`). Do not blanket-cast to `any`.

